snippet.textDisplay:
The girl that talks about inequality (Linda) has clearly no sociological background to say what she's saying. There's a reason why everyone cannot be millionaires. Infrastructures and access to quality infrastructures participate a lot in you being able to create a successful business. You can always create a great business on paper, if your current environment does not help you grow, you'll never be able to do anything.

I'm saying this because I come from a small island in the Caribbean and I always wanted to create a business. When I moved to Europe the fact of being able to move where ever you want, to be able to access seminars in other European countries etc. made it so much more easier than the island I come from. The ecosystem was just not prevalent for entrepreneurship.


Another thing is, components it life can make it very complicated e.g. having children at an early age, having many brothers and sisters or coming from a poor background. Studies show that the main reasons why minorities struggle to access the best resources (schools etc.) is because from the start due to family situations, they have to harness certain tasks that make it difficult to focus on your future (e.g. taking care of your brothers and sisters because you family can't afford child daycare or simply not having your own room to revise for exams). Most of the times too, you cannot access activities that participate in opening up your mind and skills.


It's not just a question of wanting. You need a solid environment. If your born in the USA, does not matter if you were born in a ghetto, you're still in the United States of America. Opportunities are plenty. However, if you're born in the slums of Columbia for example, resources are just not the same and access to riches is a whole lot more complicated.


There's are reason why people live their countries to have access to better resources. It's not magic.

snippet.textDisplay:
The tax question was a bad one to ask because I seriously doubt any of those millionaires are worth more than 50 million, and that's the sort of threshold that's being floated around for why the rich need to be taxed more.


The question of raising taxes on the wealthy isn't meant to penalize or go after the people who are worth 1 million, 5 million, or 10 million. It's meant for those making as low as 50 million and up to the wealthiest of the wealth, 64 billion if youre Bloomberg or 137 billion if you're Bezos. If Bloomberg suddenly has to pay 3 billion in taxes as someone worth 64 billion, would anyone in his position really notice that difference? The answer is no. It may make you blink, but when you're net worth is 21x what you would have to pay in taxes you're realistically not going to be severely affected by it.

snippet.textDisplay: For the "I know what It's like to be poor" question - I'm 16 and growing up my parents were and right now are financially dependant on the welfare system, as my father was being given $1200 a month and my mother $1000 a month, where of a family of 4 with my brother, we lived in a pretty small house and would sleep on the same bed most of the time. I wouldn't consider us poverty-level poor but given our status, I'd say we were more 'underprivileged' than most. Yet we still enjoyed it and were and still are happy with what we were given us. Yet Timothy decides that the only way to be able to experience what being 'poor' means, he travels to 3rd world countries and sees people living below the poverty line and is like "Yup, I'm pretty sure that's poor". It's not being poor, Timothy. It's called living in poverty without access to many basic human needs that most 1st world nations has so much more of.

snippet.textDisplay: "Anyone can make it" is the biggest American lie there is. It's all about opportunities and choices and not everyone will get or make good ones. That is not happening but again it is about Opportunities and choices. Plenty of people have taken the right paths to becoming CEO of a major company but they will never be one because they will not get the opportunity from others.  They might create their own company by choice but it may never be a major company based on the choices of others. Life is a matter of "us" not a matter of "I".
